Absolutely. Adding them to `settings.json` is actually the preferred way to keep a reproducible setup.

You can paste this block into your `settings.json`. If you already have some of these keys (like `files.exclude`), just merge the new entries into the existing list:

```json
{
    // üíæ File Synchronization
    "files.autoSave": "onFocusChange",

    // üîç Reducing Noise (Hides these from the sidebar and search)
    "files.exclude": {
        "**/.venv": true,
        "**/__pycache__": true,
        "**/*.egg-info": true,
        "**/.git": true
    },

    // üìú Terminal Visibility
    "terminal.integrated.scrollback": 10000,

    // üõ†Ô∏è Python/Ruff specific (from previous step)
    "[python]": {
        "editor.defaultFormatter": "charliermarsh.ruff",
        "editor.formatOnSave": true,
        "editor.codeActionsOnSave": {
            "source.fixAll.ruff": "explicit",
            "source.organizeImports.ruff": "explicit"
        }
    }
}
```

### Why these keys?
*   **`files.autoSave`**: No more manual `Ctrl+S`. Switching to the terminal triggers the save.
*   **`files.exclude`**: Keeps your workspace clean and prevents the agent from wasting tokens indexing library code in `.venv`.
*   **`terminal.integrated.scrollback`**: Ensures you can see the start of long agent responses.
*   **`editor.codeActionsOnSave`**: (Optional Addition) This tells Ruff to not just format, but also fix import order and basic linting errors every time you save.

